WEBVTT

00:07.174 --> 00:08.207
Man #1: Doctor?

00:08.209 --> 00:11.276
Man #2:
Any time today.

00:11.278 --> 00:13.579
[ Man coughing ]

00:13.581 --> 00:17.316
Hello, residents.
Dr. rorish will be here shortly.

00:17.318 --> 00:19.651
For now, you got me.

00:19.653 --> 00:21.053
I'm Jesse sallander.

00:21.055 --> 00:23.455
For the next three years,
I'm your mama.

00:23.457 --> 00:26.158
I'm the senior E.R. nurse,
and I can promise you

00:26.160 --> 00:28.427
there's nothing
that goes on in this house

00:28.429 --> 00:31.263
your mama don't know about.

00:31.265 --> 00:35.601
Try hiding something,
your mama will find out.

00:35.603 --> 00:37.603
You think you're smarter
than your mama

00:37.605 --> 00:38.804
because you got an m.D.?

00:38.806 --> 00:41.340
Well, you are not.

00:41.342 --> 00:45.044
Your mama knows when
you're lying, crying, or dying,

00:45.046 --> 00:48.147
and it's not only my job
to teach you right from wrong,

00:48.149 --> 00:51.116
but to make sure you don't
leave here in three years

00:51.118 --> 00:53.786
<i> thinking</i> you can do no wrong.

00:53.788 --> 00:55.621
Guys, can we clean this up,
please?

00:55.623 --> 00:57.423
Mario:
You resident or attending?

00:57.425 --> 00:59.691
First-year resident, like you.
My name's Christa.

00:59.693 --> 01:01.293
Mario.
Where'd you intern?

01:01.295 --> 01:02.478
Ucla.

01:02.479 --> 01:03.662
Can't beat the tuition,
right?

01:03.664 --> 01:05.147
Wouldn't know. Nyu.

01:05.148 --> 01:06.631
I'll be paying off loans
till I'm your age.

01:06.634 --> 01:08.167
Thank you.

01:08.169 --> 01:11.370
Thousands of newly minted
doctors like yourself

01:11.372 --> 01:15.107
apply every year
to learn emergency medicine

01:15.109 --> 01:20.245
in the civic cathedral,
which you are about to enter.

01:23.250 --> 01:26.385
This is why you're here.

01:27.388 --> 01:30.656
The most famous strip
of hospital real estate

01:30.658 --> 01:34.293
in the nation, where
emergency medicine was born,

01:34.295 --> 01:36.428
where the secret service
reserves a trauma bed

01:36.430 --> 01:38.797
for the president
of the United States

01:38.799 --> 01:40.499
when he is in Los Angeles.

01:40.501 --> 01:44.136
This is trauma-1,
angels memorial.

01:44.138 --> 01:46.138
These stalls
around the perimeter,

01:46.140 --> 01:49.741
which we call the sides,
are for the patients

01:49.743 --> 01:52.311
who put off dying
for a few minutes.

01:52.313 --> 01:54.613
And then this here,
this is for the ones

01:54.615 --> 01:57.416
who are trying to die on you
right this second.

01:57.418 --> 02:00.819
This, ladies and gentlemen,
is center stage.

02:00.821 --> 02:05.257
People come here for one reason
and one reason only --

02:05.259 --> 02:07.192
to get one last miracle.

02:07.194 --> 02:10.662
Now, in your mama's house,
there is a number-one rule,

02:10.664 --> 02:13.265
and in order that you properly
obey this number-one rule,

02:13.267 --> 02:15.334
ask me all the questions
you think are stupid.

02:15.336 --> 02:17.903
Why? Because you're gonna be
too afraid to ask daddy.

02:17.905 --> 02:21.874
So better to ask me than
to violate the number-one rule,

02:21.876 --> 02:26.578
which is that you are<i> not,</i>
under any circumstances,

02:26.580 --> 02:30.716
allowed to kill a guest
in my house.

02:33.687 --> 02:36.255
If he's mama,
who's daddy?

02:36.257 --> 02:37.422
[ Alarm buzzing ]

02:37.424 --> 02:38.490
Somebody's at the door!

02:38.492 --> 02:40.692
Homeboy drop-off!
Let's move!

02:40.694 --> 02:41.760
<i> That's</i> daddy.

02:41.762 --> 02:43.362
Grab some gloves,
follow me.

02:43.364 --> 02:44.980
What the hell's
a homeboy drop-off?

02:44.981 --> 02:46.597
Gangbangers leave their wounded
on the sidewalk.

02:46.600 --> 02:47.950
Jesse put up a doorbell.

02:47.951 --> 02:49.301
"Homeboy drop-off"?
That sounds racist.

02:49.303 --> 02:51.403
[ Chuckles ]<i> They</i> gave it
that name, not us.

02:51.405 --> 02:52.671
Oh, my God.

02:52.673 --> 02:53.872
Mario: What the hell?

02:53.874 --> 02:55.474
Keep it together!
Come on!

02:55.476 --> 02:58.577
Leanne: Got a heavy bleeder
up front. Check the back.

02:58.579 --> 03:00.512
Malaya: Back's empty.

03:00.513 --> 03:02.446
Gunshot wound to the neck,
obliterated carotid.

03:02.449 --> 03:03.549
He's lost
half his volume here.

03:03.551 --> 03:04.906
Jesse, we got to
get him out of here.

03:04.907 --> 03:06.262
Let's get the gurney underneath
him, please. Go.

03:06.263 --> 03:07.618
All right, you --
get over there on the other side

03:07.621 --> 03:08.854
and push with both legs.

03:08.856 --> 03:11.323
One, two, three...
Go!

03:11.325 --> 03:12.457
Put him up.

03:12.459 --> 03:13.725
Watch his head. One more time.
Let's go.

03:13.727 --> 03:14.793
One, two, three, go!

03:14.795 --> 03:17.229
All right,
you, ride up top.

03:17.798 --> 03:19.198
Malaya: I can do it.

03:19.200 --> 03:20.632
Get up there.

03:20.634 --> 03:21.934
All right,
careful, careful.

03:21.936 --> 03:23.569
Put your finger down
where my finger is, right?

03:23.571 --> 03:25.304
You feel that little thing
wiggling around like a worm

03:25.306 --> 03:26.305
trying to get away?

03:26.307 --> 03:27.907
Okay,
that's the carotid artery.

03:27.908 --> 03:29.508
Your finger is now the only
thing keeping that man alive.

03:29.510 --> 03:31.477
Okay, go.

03:31.478 --> 03:33.445
Life is measured here
in split seconds.

03:33.447 --> 03:35.881
Hesitate, and people die.

03:35.883 --> 03:37.816
I'm gonna need some suction.

03:37.818 --> 03:39.251
Ella, Ella.
Call a t.T.A.

03:39.253 --> 03:40.752
Jesse,
call the blood bank.

03:40.754 --> 03:43.488
Tell them I need 6 to 8 units
and notify the O.R.

03:43.490 --> 03:44.890
Copy that.

03:44.892 --> 03:46.425
Off to level 1,
all right.

03:46.427 --> 03:48.260
Got a gunshot wound,
male.

03:48.262 --> 03:49.494
One hole.
I don't know if there's more.

03:49.496 --> 03:50.963
N.V.P. Now!

03:52.366 --> 03:55.500
R.S.I. Etomidate.
20 milligrams.

03:55.502 --> 03:58.003
Sux 140, please.
Push it on my mark.

03:58.005 --> 03:58.904
Meds are ready.

03:58.906 --> 04:00.205
Push it now, please.

04:00.206 --> 04:01.505
Okay. Okay, now's a good time
to get down.

04:01.508 --> 04:02.674
Come on, come on.
Copy that.

04:02.676 --> 04:03.742
Do you want me
to get the labs

04:03.744 --> 04:04.943
for transfusion type
and cross match?

04:04.945 --> 04:06.411
No, but you can
take over cpr.

04:06.413 --> 04:07.746
But the blood loss is
critical.

04:07.748 --> 04:08.880
Look at his pulse, doctor.

04:08.882 --> 04:10.582
This man's heart needs
assistance.

04:10.584 --> 04:12.317
Leanne: Stop compressions
so we can intubate.

04:12.319 --> 04:14.002
You got it?
Yeah.

04:14.003 --> 04:15.686
Who can tell me why this patient
cannot be transfused

04:15.689 --> 04:17.689
with type
and cross-match blood?

04:17.691 --> 04:19.541
Anyone?

04:19.542 --> 04:21.392
'Cause it takes an hour.
He doesn't have an hour.

04:21.395 --> 04:22.828
He needs o-neg,
which is here now.

04:22.830 --> 04:24.330
Thank you, Jesse.

04:24.331 --> 04:25.831
But six units?
That's a lot of blood.

04:25.833 --> 04:27.866
By the time he gets sewn up,
he'll have lost that and more.

04:27.868 --> 04:29.835
Hang on. She's right.

04:29.837 --> 04:31.703
Yeah.

04:31.705 --> 04:33.505
It's gonna take
a vascular surgeon an hour

04:33.507 --> 04:35.274
to replace that vessel,
and he doesn't have an hour.

04:35.276 --> 04:36.475
He doesn't have 10 minutes.

04:36.476 --> 04:37.675
And all that blood's
gonna end up on the floor

04:37.678 --> 04:39.044
underneath a dead man.

04:39.046 --> 04:41.546
It's Friday night, mama.
We're gonna need that blood.

04:41.548 --> 04:42.547
Yes, we will.

04:42.549 --> 04:43.615
You're not gonna
transfuse him?

04:43.616 --> 04:44.682
Wait.
You're just gonna kill him?

04:44.685 --> 04:45.984
Neal:
What's going on?

04:48.822 --> 04:50.722
I need a vas cath
in his "l" subclavian

04:50.724 --> 04:52.691
and all the cold saline
that I can get.

04:52.693 --> 04:54.326
Leanne? A word?

04:54.327 --> 04:55.960
Who can tell me
what I'm doing?

04:55.963 --> 04:57.562
Woman: Cold saline,
coming in.

04:57.564 --> 04:59.564
Anyone?

04:59.566 --> 05:02.367
I'm replacing all the patient's
blood with ice-cold saline.

05:02.369 --> 05:03.602
Why am I doing that?

05:03.603 --> 05:04.836
You shouldn't be.
He's already decompensating.

05:04.838 --> 05:06.571
I need assistance,
Dr. Hudson.

05:06.573 --> 05:08.440
I'll take it black
with no sugar.

05:08.442 --> 05:10.375
That's a<i> man</i> on that table,
leanne.

05:10.377 --> 05:12.044
You -- are you ready
to speak yet?

05:12.046 --> 05:14.746
The theory of cold infusion
is that it can create

05:14.748 --> 05:16.848
a temporary suspension of
animation through hypothermia,

05:16.850 --> 05:18.650
buying the patient, in theory,
the hour it'll take a surgeon

05:18.652 --> 05:19.851
to repair the artery.

05:19.853 --> 05:22.054
[ Chuckles ] Bingo.
So you were right.

05:22.056 --> 05:23.388
We<i> are</i> going to kill him.

05:23.390 --> 05:25.624
We're going to kill him
to save him.

05:25.626 --> 05:28.460
All right.
Let it go, let it go.

05:28.462 --> 05:29.594
You have the cold saline?
Yep. Stat it.

05:29.596 --> 05:30.796
Jesse: Suction.

05:38.472 --> 05:41.673
A cold infusion.
It's an experimental procedure.

05:41.675 --> 05:43.775
It doesn't even have
i.R.B. Approval yet.

05:43.777 --> 05:45.244
Sounds exciting.

05:45.245 --> 05:46.712
You're the director
of the E.R., mark.

05:46.714 --> 05:47.713
Where's your concern?

05:47.715 --> 05:49.348
Left it
in a bottle of Xanax.

05:49.350 --> 05:50.716
The patient survived,
Neal.

05:50.718 --> 05:52.334
Well,<i> this</i> time.

05:52.335 --> 05:53.951
Look, it was a horrible thing
that happened to leanne.

05:53.954 --> 05:55.754
We all felt it.

05:55.756 --> 05:57.723
But in the three years since,
she's had more dropouts

05:57.725 --> 05:59.424
than any residency director
we've ever had.

05:59.426 --> 06:01.560
[ Sighs ]
She's become more dangerous
and more reckless.

06:01.562 --> 06:03.662
She's been investigated --
what -- four times by the state.

06:03.664 --> 06:05.097
Exonerated four times.

06:05.099 --> 06:07.532
I mean, where are we going
with this?

06:07.534 --> 06:09.735
She's different.
You know she is.

06:09.737 --> 06:13.472
No, what I know is that while
the accident was deeply tragic,

06:13.474 --> 06:15.507
all that rage
made her better.

06:15.509 --> 06:17.476
You know,
more dropouts, yes,

06:17.478 --> 06:19.644
but the ones
that got through her

06:19.646 --> 06:22.881
went on to better jobs
at better hospitals.

06:22.883 --> 06:24.816
She makes great docs,
Neal.

06:24.818 --> 06:27.652
The board likes her,
which means I<i> love</i> her.

06:27.654 --> 06:29.121
[ Knock on door ]

06:30.624 --> 06:32.591
You wanted to see me?

06:32.592 --> 06:34.559
Uh, yeah. You put a patient
into suspended animation.

06:34.561 --> 06:37.396
How's he doing? Has he, uh,
reached hyperspace yet?

06:37.398 --> 06:38.997
He's in the O.R.,
getting his carotid sewn up.

06:38.999 --> 06:40.832
And all of his blood
is safely back inside him.

06:40.834 --> 06:42.901
don't ever challenge me
in front of my residents again.

06:42.903 --> 06:44.603
You were performing
an unapproved procedure
on a patient, leanne.

06:44.605 --> 06:47.439
Uh, Neal, your old lady here,
she's, uh, trying to get up.

06:47.441 --> 06:50.075
Miss? Miss,
you can't do that, okay?

06:50.077 --> 06:52.544
The patient was in the grave.
And I brought him back.

06:52.546 --> 06:53.912
That's a win
in anyone's book.

06:53.914 --> 06:55.180
Not yours.

06:55.182 --> 06:56.448
You know,
when I was a resident,

06:56.449 --> 06:57.715
you always said
they're not scorecards.

06:57.718 --> 06:58.750
They're actual people.

06:58.752 --> 07:00.708
Careful.

07:00.709 --> 07:02.665
I think I know
a little bit better than you

07:02.666 --> 07:04.622
that kid is an actual person,
that he has an actual family

07:04.625 --> 07:07.859
who's praying that if their son
gets brought in here e.S.I.-1,

07:07.861 --> 07:09.828
he'll be treated by a doctor
who will do everything

07:09.830 --> 07:11.863
humanly possible
to save his kid's life,

07:11.865 --> 07:14.566
not by a timid one who's more
concerned about the rules

07:14.568 --> 07:16.468
than he is about the life
on the table in front of him.

07:16.470 --> 07:18.670
I see.
They want you, not me.

07:18.672 --> 07:21.706
No. You're the doctor
they want.

07:21.708 --> 07:23.008
I'm the doctor they<i> need.</i>

07:24.178 --> 07:25.977
Fun stuff,
but I just got a text

07:25.979 --> 07:27.679
that 40 people
just checked in

07:27.681 --> 07:29.181
while we were having
this little ménage,

07:29.183 --> 07:30.882
so if nobody's
taking their clothes off,

07:30.884 --> 07:33.652
I need you both
back down on the floor now.

07:33.654 --> 07:36.087
Neal, your patient.

07:41.695 --> 07:43.695
You were a little rough
on him, huh?

07:43.697 --> 07:46.498
We're not their friend,
their family, or their shrink.

07:46.500 --> 07:48.533
We're their doctor.
He gets confused.

07:48.535 --> 07:49.968
He's not confused.

07:49.970 --> 07:53.939
He cares --
about you, about them.

07:53.941 --> 07:57.509
And for that,
you have only yourself to blame.

08:07.488 --> 08:09.254
[ Indistinct talking ]

08:15.062 --> 08:16.261
Fall off your board?

08:16.263 --> 08:18.964
The rail was sketchy.
I think it's broken.

08:18.966 --> 08:21.233
I can feel bones
crunching around in there.

08:21.235 --> 08:23.068
You high right now?

08:23.070 --> 08:24.536
Why? You want some?

08:24.538 --> 08:26.771
Cute. Come on.

08:26.773 --> 08:29.140
You're only as good
as your wait time out here.

08:29.142 --> 08:31.910
You want to love your patients,
fine -- thank you --

08:31.912 --> 08:33.845
but you better love
the ones out here just as much,

08:33.847 --> 08:36.181
because
they may need you more.

08:36.183 --> 08:37.082
Angus Leighton.

08:37.084 --> 08:38.967
Malaya pineda.

08:38.968 --> 08:40.851
Wait. You're
Mike Leighton's brother?

08:40.854 --> 08:41.953
He talked about you.

08:41.955 --> 08:43.605
You know him?

08:43.606 --> 08:45.256
I was just a med student
when he was a resident,

08:45.259 --> 08:46.558
but everyone knew Mike.

08:46.560 --> 08:47.692
He's a superstar.

08:47.694 --> 08:49.895
He crapped his bed
in summer camp.

08:49.897 --> 08:51.780
He was 12, but it counts.

08:51.781 --> 08:53.664
We separate them into
three categories of acuity --

08:53.667 --> 08:55.200
e.S.I.-1, 2, and 3.

08:55.202 --> 08:56.968
E.S.I.-1 is critical.

08:56.970 --> 08:58.236
Bullet wound, heart attack.

08:58.238 --> 09:01.239
The 2 is rough,
but it's not death's door --

09:01.241 --> 09:02.574
pneumonia, blood clot.

09:02.576 --> 09:04.709
E.S.I.-3 -- meh.

09:04.711 --> 09:06.912
The flu, migraine,
minor laceration.

09:06.914 --> 09:09.180
Are we gonna be seeing
our own patients today?

09:09.182 --> 09:11.149
For now,
you'll be taking light cases

09:11.151 --> 09:12.684
and assisting the attendings

09:12.686 --> 09:14.586
unless that board says
"code black,"

09:14.588 --> 09:16.154
in which case,
half of L.A. is in this room,

09:16.156 --> 09:17.188
and then all bets are off.

09:17.190 --> 09:19.758
Doctors.
75-year-old male.

09:19.760 --> 09:21.026
Started speaking gibberish
at dinner.

09:21.028 --> 09:21.993
Bay number 4.

09:21.995 --> 09:22.928
He's gonna need t.P.A.

09:22.930 --> 09:24.095
Dr. Leighton.

09:24.097 --> 09:26.131
T.P.A.
I think he needs t.P.A.

09:26.133 --> 09:28.900
I didn't ask, but I'm sure
Dr. Guthrie will be thrilled.

09:28.902 --> 09:30.802
Follow him
and try not to kill anyone.

09:30.804 --> 09:32.871
Dr. rorish, I'd really like
to observe that case, too.

09:32.873 --> 09:34.373
How nice for you.

09:34.374 --> 09:35.874
Waiting for a formal invitation?
Go -- now.

09:35.876 --> 09:37.742
Jesse:
I'm gonna need you at dispatch.

09:37.744 --> 09:39.311
I got two coming in,
one critical.

09:39.313 --> 09:41.746
Dr. Hudson's on his way down now
to meet you.

09:41.748 --> 09:43.048
You and you --
follow me.

09:43.050 --> 09:47.919
Jesse, find something
for Dr. pineda.

09:47.921 --> 09:49.371
Why is she
ignoring me?

09:49.372 --> 09:50.822
Because you're the only one
who went to school here.

09:50.824 --> 09:52.724
It's their first day
around her.

09:52.726 --> 09:53.758
You need to relax.

09:53.760 --> 09:54.793
I'm not here to relax.

09:54.795 --> 09:55.794
I want --
i know.

09:55.796 --> 09:56.929
This is your big

09:56.930 --> 09:58.063
"I'm a doctor now" moment?

09:58.065 --> 09:59.097
Kinda, yeah.

09:59.099 --> 10:01.633
Good, good,
'cause I need a hero.

10:01.635 --> 10:04.135
In fact, I'm holding out
for a hero

10:04.137 --> 10:06.171
till the end
of the night.

10:06.173 --> 10:09.307
¶ And she gotta be fast
and she gotta be strong ¶

10:09.309 --> 10:11.610
¶ and she gotta be
fresh from the fight ¶

10:11.612 --> 10:12.911
don't get shy now.

10:12.913 --> 10:14.112
¶ I need a hero ¶

10:14.114 --> 10:15.347
come on.

10:15.349 --> 10:17.882
Come on. Let's go find you
an attending to annoy.

10:17.884 --> 10:19.217
Someone who...

10:19.219 --> 10:21.786
¶ Needs a hero! ¶

10:21.788 --> 10:23.021
looking for a hero.

10:23.023 --> 10:24.389
[ Radio chatter ]

10:24.391 --> 10:26.258
Neal: Leanne?

10:26.259 --> 10:28.126
Dr. Hudson. Say hello
to doctors savetti and lorenson.

10:28.128 --> 10:30.328
Neal Hudson. Congratulations
on matching to angels.

10:30.330 --> 10:31.896
You're learning
from the best.

10:31.898 --> 10:33.098
I didn't mean
what I said before.

10:33.100 --> 10:34.366
I don't think
those things about you.

10:34.368 --> 10:35.701
Yes, you do.

10:35.702 --> 10:37.035
Well, we just have
different philosophies.

10:37.037 --> 10:37.869
We didn't always,
leanne.

10:37.871 --> 10:39.521
What you got?

10:39.522 --> 10:41.172
Medic #1: 36-year-old male.
Airbag malfunction.

10:41.174 --> 10:43.174
Nonresponsive, head injury,
multiple lacs.

10:43.176 --> 10:44.943
Pulse 65,
b.P. 120 over 90.

10:44.944 --> 10:46.711
Medic #2:
Ariel -- multiple lacs to
the face, head, and upper body,

10:46.713 --> 10:47.779
with glass embedded
just about everywhere.

10:47.781 --> 10:48.780
She is highly agitated.

10:48.782 --> 10:49.781
Daddy! Daddy!

10:49.783 --> 10:51.266
Neal: Hey!
Whoa, whoa, whoa.

10:51.267 --> 10:52.750
No, no, no, no, no!
Darling, please!

10:52.753 --> 10:53.652
Let go of me!

10:53.654 --> 10:54.319
No.
Is he gonna die?

10:54.321 --> 10:56.121
No way.

10:56.122 --> 10:57.922
Do you want it straight
or do you want doctor talk?

10:57.924 --> 10:58.990
I want it straight.

10:58.992 --> 11:00.325
What's your name?
Ariel.

11:00.327 --> 11:02.761
Ariel, I'm Dr. rorish,
and the truth is

11:02.763 --> 11:04.095
we don't know why
your father's unconscious,

11:04.097 --> 11:05.764
and I can't learn anything
out here in the dark.

11:05.766 --> 11:08.833
So, with your permission,
i want to take him inside,

11:08.835 --> 11:10.802
and I promise you I will
tell you everything I know

11:10.804 --> 11:11.936
as soon as I know it.

11:11.938 --> 11:12.837
Okay?
Okay.

11:12.839 --> 11:14.039
Okay.

11:14.941 --> 11:16.074
You.

11:16.076 --> 11:18.209
don't ever lie
to a patient again.

11:18.211 --> 11:21.079
She may be young,
but she's entitled to the truth.

11:21.081 --> 11:23.782
One, two, three.
And careful.

11:23.784 --> 11:26.785
All right. And great.
Back down easy now.

11:26.787 --> 11:27.803
There we go.

11:27.804 --> 11:28.820
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]

11:28.822 --> 11:31.389
Pulse is thready.
B.P. 60 over 30.

11:31.391 --> 11:33.291
All right, I need central lines
prepped for pressors, please.

11:33.293 --> 11:34.025
Norepinephrine?

11:34.027 --> 11:35.176
Yes, please.

11:35.177 --> 11:36.326
Man #1: Somebody
call X-Ray, please.

11:36.329 --> 11:37.228
Man #2: I'm on it.

11:37.230 --> 11:39.330
Thank you.

11:39.332 --> 11:41.199
What's your evaluation,
doctor?

11:41.201 --> 11:45.003
Uh, patient unconscious,
low b.P., warm extremities.

11:45.005 --> 11:46.204
He's in spinal shock.

11:46.206 --> 11:47.706
No additional examination?

11:47.708 --> 11:48.940
It's pretty textbook.

11:48.942 --> 11:50.375
Pretty textbook, huh?
Yeah.

11:50.377 --> 11:52.277
Okay, what about you, doctor?
Textbook?

11:55.849 --> 11:57.015
Woman:
Here you go, needle.

11:57.017 --> 11:58.483
Thank you. Got it.

11:58.485 --> 11:59.217
Wire.

11:59.219 --> 12:00.018
Wire.

12:03.724 --> 12:04.889
Is he 1-1-1?

12:04.891 --> 12:06.758
Yes.
Then say so.

12:06.760 --> 12:10.261
Trepidation is a deadly quality
in this place.

12:10.263 --> 12:11.162
Let me out.

12:11.164 --> 12:13.181
Life lesson.

12:13.182 --> 12:15.199
When asked if you want to
examine your patient some more,

12:15.202 --> 12:17.435
it's like being asked
if you want a breath mint.

12:17.437 --> 12:19.437
The only answer is "yes."

12:20.440 --> 12:21.473
Mario: Okay, we're in.

12:21.475 --> 12:23.208
What the hell is a 1-1-1?

12:23.209 --> 12:24.942
I assumed she was referring
to the g.C.S. Scale.

12:24.945 --> 12:26.511
6-5-4 is
normal brain function.

12:26.513 --> 12:28.780
1-1-1 is the lowest.

12:28.782 --> 12:30.248
He's brain-dead.

12:30.250 --> 12:31.750
[ Sighs ]

12:31.752 --> 12:33.451
That poor kid.

12:35.922 --> 12:38.990
Neal: You know, Ariel, I think
it's time you called your aunt.

12:38.992 --> 12:41.159
She can't get a flight
until tomorrow.

12:42.863 --> 12:45.797
I can't talk to her
until I know my dad's okay.

12:45.799 --> 12:48.900
She didn't handle my mom dying
very well.

12:52.272 --> 12:55.073
How did<i> you</i> handle it?

12:55.075 --> 12:57.942
I was only 8, so...

12:59.179 --> 13:01.946
Is that lady doctor
coming in soon?

13:01.948 --> 13:03.248
The one
taking care of my dad.

13:03.250 --> 13:04.883
I'll check.

13:04.885 --> 13:08.386
Meantime,
here's my cellphone.

13:08.388 --> 13:10.488
You call your aunt.

13:10.490 --> 13:12.891
She'll feel better
hearing your voice.

13:17.230 --> 13:19.898
He was confused
that I didn't understand him.

13:19.900 --> 13:21.366
Yes.

13:21.367 --> 13:22.833
Called expressive aphasia.

13:22.836 --> 13:23.368
It's word salad.

13:23.370 --> 13:25.069
Sounds right to him,

13:25.071 --> 13:27.005
but the words come out
all tossed around.

13:29.142 --> 13:31.109
Activate the stroke team,
please.

13:31.111 --> 13:33.878
Young squire.
I heard you mention t.P.A.

13:33.880 --> 13:34.879
Is that
what you're thinking?

13:34.881 --> 13:36.347
...sides, north 4.

13:37.317 --> 13:38.850
8:55 P.M.

13:38.852 --> 13:40.251
Yes.

13:40.253 --> 13:42.353
The symptom profile suggests
m.C.A. Distribution.

13:42.355 --> 13:44.055
I think so, too.

13:44.057 --> 13:45.557
Fingers crossed.

13:45.559 --> 13:47.258
Okay,
Mr. and Mrs. cleery,

13:47.260 --> 13:50.461
t.P.A. Is a kind of miracle drug
that has the potential

13:50.463 --> 13:53.164
to bust the clot up
and reverse the stroke,

13:53.166 --> 13:56.267
but only if there's no actual
bleeding yet in the brain.

13:56.269 --> 13:57.969
We're gonna need a scan
to know for sure.

13:57.971 --> 14:00.271
Doesn't take 12 people
to run a scan.

14:00.273 --> 14:01.539
Come on, folks.
It's Friday night.

14:01.541 --> 14:04.609
Let's divide and conquer.

14:04.611 --> 14:07.846
Young squire, would you check in
at the nursing station,

14:07.848 --> 14:10.949
see where
you can be useful?

14:10.951 --> 14:12.617
When they're done
x-raying him,

14:12.619 --> 14:15.286
take him down to sides
and put a cast on him.

14:15.288 --> 14:16.154
Are you good?

14:16.156 --> 14:17.288
A cast? That's it?

14:17.290 --> 14:18.022
This one.

14:18.024 --> 14:19.958
Oh. You got it.

14:19.960 --> 14:21.559
Wait.
Where is X-Ray?

14:25.999 --> 14:28.967
Let's just keep that
between us, okay?

14:37.010 --> 14:38.509
Leanne:
He's brain-dead.

14:38.511 --> 14:40.078
Oh, God.

14:40.080 --> 14:42.347
And she's all alone
till tomorrow.

14:42.349 --> 14:44.115
Has someone called
child and family services

14:44.117 --> 14:45.750
to come get her?

14:45.751 --> 14:47.384
Yeah, but you know how
that goes. It could be hours.

14:47.387 --> 14:49.020
[ Inhales sharply ]

14:49.022 --> 14:50.488
It gets worse.

14:50.490 --> 14:52.590
He's an organ donor.

14:52.592 --> 14:54.242
Transplant team's
on the way.

14:54.243 --> 14:55.893
Then we can't wait for cfs.
I have to tell her.

14:55.896 --> 14:57.161
Neal.

14:57.163 --> 14:58.496
Neal.

15:00.600 --> 15:03.067
<i> I</i> should do it.

15:03.069 --> 15:05.470
Why?
She's my patient.

15:05.472 --> 15:08.006
I gave her my word.

15:08.008 --> 15:10.308
I don't think it's a good idea.
It won't be pretty.

15:10.310 --> 15:12.644
Are you protecting<i> me</i>
or<i> her?</i>

15:12.646 --> 15:14.379
He was under my care.

15:14.381 --> 15:16.180
Let's do it together.

15:20.453 --> 15:21.519
[ Curtain opens ]

15:21.521 --> 15:22.687
Is he awake?

15:24.457 --> 15:28.026
Ariel, your father came in
with some terrible injuries,

15:28.028 --> 15:30.495
most of which
we couldn't see at first.

15:30.497 --> 15:32.196
What are you...

15:32.198 --> 15:33.631
What are you saying?

15:34.601 --> 15:36.668
There is no g--

15:38.071 --> 15:40.204
...good way to say this.

15:40.206 --> 15:41.539
I'm sorry.

15:41.541 --> 15:43.274
For what?

15:46.079 --> 15:47.679
We couldn't save him.

15:47.681 --> 15:50.415
I-i don't understand.

15:50.417 --> 15:52.617
Neal:
Your father died, Ariel.

15:52.619 --> 15:54.319
Well, technically --

15:54.321 --> 15:57.488
technically,
it's a-a brain death.

15:57.490 --> 16:00.124
So he's not dead?
No, no. That's --

16:00.126 --> 16:02.060
what I mean is,

16:02.061 --> 16:03.995
machines are keeping his body
in a state of --

16:03.997 --> 16:05.096
what are you saying?

16:05.098 --> 16:06.698
I'm trying
to explain to you.

16:06.699 --> 16:08.299
No, you're not! What happened to
just giving it to me straight?

16:08.301 --> 16:10.168
I'm giving it to you
straight.

16:10.169 --> 16:12.036
So he's dead, but technically,
not really, right?

16:12.038 --> 16:13.504
No, I want to go see him.
I want to see him.

16:13.506 --> 16:14.672
I have to see him!

16:14.674 --> 16:17.275
Please, sit down.
Please sit.

16:17.277 --> 16:19.194
Listen.
No.

16:19.195 --> 16:21.112
Ariel, your father
chose to be an organ donor.

16:21.114 --> 16:24.615
That's why we have machines
keeping his organs functioning.

16:24.617 --> 16:26.584
You have to understand --
he's never going to wake up.

16:26.586 --> 16:29.020
He's gone, sweetheart.

16:29.022 --> 16:30.455
I'm terribly sorry.

16:32.058 --> 16:34.325
[ Voice breaking ]
No.

16:34.327 --> 16:35.293
No.

16:36.396 --> 16:37.595
No.

16:37.597 --> 16:38.329
Ariel.

16:38.331 --> 16:39.263
No.

16:39.265 --> 16:41.065
No, I know.

16:41.067 --> 16:43.201
No, no, no.

16:43.203 --> 16:45.303
You can't have his organs.

16:45.305 --> 16:47.372
I'm his daughter,
and I'm saying no.

16:47.374 --> 16:50.441
Well, unfortunately, that's not
your decision to make.

16:50.443 --> 16:52.010
It's your father's,
and he made it a long time ago.

16:52.012 --> 16:53.044
No, you don't care
about my father,

16:53.046 --> 16:55.179
and you don't care
about me.

16:55.181 --> 16:56.514
You just want
to cut him up.

16:56.516 --> 16:57.248
[ Clattering ]

16:57.250 --> 16:59.450
That is not true.

16:59.452 --> 17:02.253
Shut up! Shut up.

17:02.255 --> 17:04.389
[ Sobbing ]

17:08.395 --> 17:09.560
Sorry.

17:09.562 --> 17:10.728
I'm...

17:10.730 --> 17:12.530
I'm so sorry.

17:12.532 --> 17:14.432
[ Sobs ]
Shh.

17:19.239 --> 17:22.306
¶¶

17:29.516 --> 17:34.085
[ indistinct talking ]

17:34.087 --> 17:37.255
Man: Got bleeding,
I've got bleeding!

17:43.229 --> 17:46.364
[ Wheels rattling ]

17:46.366 --> 17:49.067
[ Indistinct talking ]

17:53.273 --> 17:55.239
[ Monitor beeping ]

18:04.317 --> 18:07.552
Jesse:
Transplant team's en route.

18:07.554 --> 18:10.655
I want to tell you
how fabulous you look right now.

18:10.657 --> 18:12.156
I do?

18:12.158 --> 18:14.292
No. I want to tell you that,
but then it'd be a lie.

18:14.294 --> 18:17.195
You look like you've been
strapped to the bow of a ship.

18:17.197 --> 18:18.096
Is that so?

18:18.098 --> 18:19.363
Mm-hmm.

18:19.365 --> 18:20.565
[ Laughs ]

18:20.567 --> 18:22.400
No, no. don't do that.

18:22.402 --> 18:24.402
You don't need any more
laugh lines, believe me.

18:24.404 --> 18:26.170
Me? Have you looked at yourself
in the mirror lately?

18:26.172 --> 18:27.672
Mm-hmm.

18:29.676 --> 18:32.176
I love you so much,
i want to break you in half.

18:32.178 --> 18:35.413
I love you so much,
i want to punch your face in.

18:35.415 --> 18:37.281
[ Both chuckle ]

18:37.283 --> 18:39.183
All right, back to work.

18:39.185 --> 18:41.119
We might hit code black
tonight.

18:41.121 --> 18:42.787
You got that, boss.

18:47.794 --> 18:49.894
Well, you qualify for t.P.A.,
and we're still

18:49.896 --> 18:51.863
inside the window
for it to be effective.

18:51.865 --> 18:54.232
What are
the complications?

18:54.234 --> 18:56.601
Only 7%
experience the miracle.

18:56.603 --> 18:58.603
However,
the same number experience

18:58.605 --> 19:01.339
catastrophic bleeding
somewhere else in the body.

19:01.341 --> 19:03.574
We wouldn't know where
until it was actually happening,

19:03.576 --> 19:06.310
and we might not
be able to stop it.

19:06.312 --> 19:07.912
And if we do nothing?

19:07.914 --> 19:09.680
What you see now.

19:09.682 --> 19:11.349
And possibly worse.

19:16.356 --> 19:19.357
Hey, Hannah?
Who's next?

19:19.359 --> 19:21.526
Uh...26 year old...

19:21.528 --> 19:23.361
Pregnant, u.R.I.,
fever.

19:23.363 --> 19:24.495
Parked her in triage.

19:24.497 --> 19:25.530
Sounds like the flu.

19:25.532 --> 19:27.165
Evaluate,
then come find me.

19:27.167 --> 19:28.900
Should I go --
evaluate and find me.

19:28.902 --> 19:30.835
Next.

19:31.838 --> 19:33.171
How do you know
so much?

19:33.173 --> 19:34.973
Believe me, I don't.

19:34.974 --> 19:36.774
We both went to medical school,
we both did an internship.

19:36.776 --> 19:38.242
You pulling
second residency?

19:38.244 --> 19:39.577
What do you mean?

19:39.578 --> 19:40.911
I mean, were you already an m.D.
And then went back

19:40.914 --> 19:42.413
to try a different specialty
or something?

19:42.415 --> 19:44.782
No. I was too busy
being a wife and a mom.

19:44.784 --> 19:47.451
Wife and a mom?
You sure you're ready for this?

19:47.453 --> 19:48.653
How old
do you think I am?

19:49.789 --> 19:51.205
[ Chuckles ]

19:51.206 --> 19:52.622
All I'm saying is,
there's no tougher place to work

19:52.625 --> 19:55.226
in all of E.R. medicine than
trauma-1 at angels memorial.

19:55.228 --> 19:56.661
This place is
hard enough for...

19:56.663 --> 19:58.796
The young.

19:58.798 --> 20:00.531
For the unattached.

20:00.533 --> 20:01.899
Stop being threatened
by me, okay?

20:01.900 --> 20:03.266
Is that what you think,
that I'm threatened?

20:03.269 --> 20:05.503
I think we should
examine this patient together.

20:05.505 --> 20:08.573
Maybe we'll both
learn something.

20:08.575 --> 20:09.874
Why not?

20:09.876 --> 20:11.309
The worst part is
the headache.

20:11.311 --> 20:12.877
I live above the boiler room
in my building,

20:12.879 --> 20:14.712
and the noise just keeps
cracking my head open.

20:14.714 --> 20:16.280
Is there anything
you can give me for that?

20:16.282 --> 20:17.915
You're
nine months pregnant.

20:17.916 --> 20:19.549
There's not a whole lot we can
do other than give you Tylenol.

20:19.552 --> 20:21.886
I've tried that.
Doesn't work.

20:21.888 --> 20:23.287
Using again?

20:23.289 --> 20:24.855
Excuse me?
Mario.

20:24.857 --> 20:26.224
The scars on the inside
of your arm --

20:26.226 --> 20:27.258
they're old track marks,
right?

20:27.260 --> 20:28.993
None of your damn business.

20:28.995 --> 20:30.728
Who the hell
do you think you are?

20:30.729 --> 20:32.462
Just a doctor trying to figure
out what's wrong with a patient.

20:32.465 --> 20:34.432
You're a jackass.
I don't have to listen to this.

20:34.434 --> 20:36.500
[ Coughing ]
Take it easy.
Take it easy.

20:36.502 --> 20:37.635
It's okay.
He's leaving.

20:37.637 --> 20:40.304
Can I talk to you
for a second?

20:40.306 --> 20:41.639
What was that about?

20:41.641 --> 20:43.074
She's a seeker.

20:43.075 --> 20:44.508
Heroin withdrawals
often mimic flu symptoms.

20:44.510 --> 20:45.676
You don't know that
for a fact.

20:45.678 --> 20:47.595
Where's the fever?

20:47.596 --> 20:49.513
If it was the flu, would've
hit her like a freight train.

20:49.515 --> 20:51.515
You got a lot of experience
with drug withdrawals?

20:51.517 --> 20:53.251
No. I'm sorry. I just don't
think that woman is using.

20:53.253 --> 20:55.586
I know a little bit more
about this than you do.

20:55.588 --> 20:57.288
It was a long time ago.
I'm not ashamed.

20:57.290 --> 20:59.724
I pulled myself out,
and I'm fine now.

20:59.726 --> 21:02.260
What, do you two just not have
enough to do?

21:02.262 --> 21:03.794
We're having a disagreement
about a patient.

21:03.796 --> 21:04.662
Oh, yeah? Which one?

21:04.664 --> 21:05.730
The pregnant u.R.I.

21:05.731 --> 21:06.797
I think we should run
a tox screen,

21:06.799 --> 21:07.932
rule out
heroin withdrawals.

21:07.934 --> 21:09.400
Huh. And you?

21:09.402 --> 21:10.952
I don't know.
Something's not right.

21:10.953 --> 21:12.503
I don't think it's the flu,
i don't think it's heroin.

21:12.505 --> 21:13.938
If I just had a little bit
more time, I could --

21:13.940 --> 21:16.641
well, you don't have time,
and a positive tox screen

21:16.643 --> 21:18.776
doesn't change
the management of the case.

21:18.778 --> 21:20.411
Even if she has
an addiction problem,

21:20.413 --> 21:22.046
there is nothing
we can do for her in the E.R.

21:22.048 --> 21:24.515
Recommend a social worker,
ship her out.

21:25.985 --> 21:27.585
You make a good point
about the fever,

21:27.587 --> 21:28.819
but I don't think
it's heroin.

21:28.821 --> 21:30.454
Doesn't matter.
You heard what she said.

21:30.456 --> 21:31.956
Doesn't change
the management of the case.

21:31.957 --> 21:33.457
Yeah, but we need to know.
We should run a tox screen.

21:33.459 --> 21:35.059
There's no "we" here.
You heard what rorish said.

21:35.061 --> 21:37.662
She also said
trepidation is a deadly quality.

21:37.664 --> 21:39.664
I'm already on her bad side.
There's nothing in this for me.

21:39.666 --> 21:41.065
Except maybe
saving a patient's life.

21:41.067 --> 21:43.034
Malaya, whatever you're doing,
log out, follow me.

21:43.036 --> 21:44.535
You're gonna love this.

21:44.537 --> 21:46.470
Sounds exciting.

21:46.472 --> 21:48.673
Clearly, you don't speak the
native tongue of my people --

21:48.675 --> 21:50.508
sarcasm. Come on.

21:50.510 --> 21:52.677
Hey, come on.
Hold your arm up just like this.

21:52.679 --> 21:54.279
Angus.
Yep?

21:54.280 --> 21:55.880
Guthrie wants you.
He's with the stroke patient.

21:55.882 --> 21:58.132
Malaya can finish
the cast.

21:58.133 --> 22:00.383
Wait. Guthrie's gonna let him
administer the t.P.A.?

22:00.386 --> 22:02.386
And I'm gonna do
a nurse's job?

22:02.388 --> 22:03.821
A nurse's job?

22:03.823 --> 22:05.923
I didn't mean it.

22:05.925 --> 22:07.458
You want to be
part of a team, Malaya,

22:07.460 --> 22:09.393
no job is too big,
no job is too small.

22:09.395 --> 22:10.561
Dr. Leighton,
go now, please.

22:10.563 --> 22:11.929
Yep.

22:11.931 --> 22:13.964
Arm up. Come on.

22:13.966 --> 22:15.733
I won't go, either.

22:15.735 --> 22:17.251
That's ridiculous.

22:17.252 --> 22:18.768
I didn't mean it.
Of course I'm going.

22:18.771 --> 22:20.371
Wait. What's up
with skater boy?

22:20.373 --> 22:22.406
He's, uh...

22:22.408 --> 22:23.541
Just sleeping it off.

22:23.543 --> 22:25.109
Great.

22:25.111 --> 22:27.111
Go. T.P.A. Has
a short window.

22:36.789 --> 22:39.857
How soon will we know
if it worked?

22:39.859 --> 22:43.361
Just takes a few seconds --
when it works.

23:05.418 --> 23:07.418
Come on, baby.

23:07.420 --> 23:10.621
Show us the magic.

23:15.094 --> 23:16.527
Mr. cleery.

23:17.897 --> 23:20.431
I want you
to try and speak.

23:33.780 --> 23:35.579
[ Voice breaking ]
Love you.

23:35.581 --> 23:37.815
[ Crying ] Yes.

23:39.619 --> 23:41.752
Abracadabra.

23:41.754 --> 23:45.156
That's why we're here,
young squire.

23:45.158 --> 23:47.124
Never forget that.

23:52.031 --> 23:54.632
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]

23:58.905 --> 24:01.172
[ Screams ]

24:01.174 --> 24:03.474
Take it easy!
Take it easy!
No! No! No!

24:03.476 --> 24:05.009
Medic: 10-year-old male,
breathing labored,

24:05.011 --> 24:06.878
possible allergic reaction.

24:06.879 --> 24:08.746
[ Norwegian accent ]
He didn't eat or drink
anything out of the ordinary.

24:08.748 --> 24:09.647
Uh,
where are you from?

24:09.649 --> 24:10.181
Norway.

24:10.183 --> 24:11.715
Uh, center stage.

24:11.717 --> 24:13.884
Your son has a collapsed lung.
We're gonna help.

24:13.886 --> 24:15.519
How could you know that?

24:15.521 --> 24:18.122
If a Norwegian kid can't
breathe, it's a pneumothorax.

24:18.124 --> 24:19.723
It's a genetic
predisposition.

24:19.725 --> 24:21.792
Can someone run another I.V.
For me, please?

24:21.794 --> 24:23.027
Jesse:
I'm all out of nurses.

24:23.029 --> 24:24.728
I got it!
My girl.

24:24.730 --> 24:26.096
Okay, watch his head.

24:26.098 --> 24:27.131
Medic: Ready?

24:27.133 --> 24:28.833
Back him up,
back him up.

24:28.835 --> 24:30.701
What's your son's name?

24:30.703 --> 24:32.069
Basti --
short for "Sebastian."

24:32.071 --> 24:34.939
Okay, basti.

24:34.941 --> 24:36.474
I need you to look at me.

24:36.476 --> 24:37.174
Need a mask.

24:37.176 --> 24:38.809
Step it out.
Step it out.

24:38.811 --> 24:40.261
You're gonna be
all right.

24:40.262 --> 24:41.712
We just need to let a little air
out of your chest.

24:41.714 --> 24:42.847
You're gonna feel better
right away.

24:42.849 --> 24:43.981
Jesse: It's okay.

24:43.983 --> 24:44.966
Leanne, transplant team

24:44.967 --> 24:45.950
just took Ariel's father
upstairs.

24:45.952 --> 24:47.117
Understood.

24:47.119 --> 24:49.920
Uh, we're gonna put a tube
into basti's chest

24:49.922 --> 24:51.489
to relieve the pressure.

24:51.491 --> 24:54.859
This is very routine.
We can do it right here.

24:54.861 --> 24:56.026
She asked
to talk to you.

24:56.028 --> 24:56.861
Me? Why?

24:56.863 --> 24:57.895
She connected with you.

24:57.897 --> 24:59.263
No, she didn't.

24:59.265 --> 25:00.648
Uh, nurse.

25:00.649 --> 25:02.032
Angus, you're gonna do
the chest tube.

25:02.034 --> 25:02.900
Me?

25:02.902 --> 25:04.168
Yes.

25:06.005 --> 25:07.004
What are you doing?

25:07.006 --> 25:08.289
I'm looking for my diploma

25:08.290 --> 25:09.573
to make sure
it's really my name on it.

25:09.575 --> 25:10.741
I'm prepping a tray
for you.

25:10.743 --> 25:12.243
You're going to be making
an incision.

25:12.245 --> 25:13.338
Media:
I need some more local.

25:13.339 --> 25:14.432
Neal: Leanne,
i can take this case.

25:14.433 --> 25:15.526
Go and talk to her
for a minute.

25:15.527 --> 25:16.620
Look, if you want me to be
a social worker,

25:16.621 --> 25:17.714
you pick the patient who should
die in the waiting room.

25:17.717 --> 25:20.284
She's a patient, too, leanne.
Go and talk to her for a minute.

25:20.286 --> 25:21.952
Look around you, doctor!
We're about to be in code black.

25:21.954 --> 25:24.822
I have eczema,
itches like crazy.

25:24.824 --> 25:26.824
You don't care, right?

25:26.825 --> 25:28.825
These people here, they don't
care about your problems either.

25:28.828 --> 25:30.761
All right,
uh, Sebastian,

25:30.763 --> 25:32.530
I want you to slow
your breathing down, okay?

25:32.532 --> 25:33.898
Can you do that?

25:33.900 --> 25:37.167
Man:
We're going to help you.

25:37.169 --> 25:38.903
Woman: What's that kid
doing in here?

25:38.905 --> 25:40.638
Is he okay?
Whose patient is this?

25:40.640 --> 25:42.172
Mine.

25:42.174 --> 25:43.574
Hey. Focus.

25:44.777 --> 25:45.910
Whoa!

25:45.912 --> 25:48.045
This kid
has a head injury!

25:48.047 --> 25:48.946
I need a gurney.

25:48.948 --> 25:50.314
I'm out of gurneys.

25:50.316 --> 25:51.916
Guys, guys, can I get
a wheelchair? Come on.

25:51.918 --> 25:54.785
A wheelchair or something.

25:54.787 --> 25:56.820
[ Indistinct talking ]

25:56.822 --> 25:58.322
I got to pull somebody
out of here.

25:58.324 --> 25:59.924
Medic:
I.V. Tubing.

25:59.926 --> 26:03.060
[ Indistinct talking continues ]

26:03.062 --> 26:05.729
We are officially
in code black.

26:05.731 --> 26:07.064
God help us.

26:07.066 --> 26:09.600
[ Monitor beeping ]

26:16.809 --> 26:20.144
Leanne:
Yeah, exactly. That's what
we need -- a neurosurgeon.

26:20.146 --> 26:22.780
Yeah, of course we're gonna
get a C.T. scan, Natalie,

26:22.782 --> 26:24.582
as soon as the room frees.

26:24.584 --> 26:26.117
No, I know it is,

26:26.118 --> 26:27.651
but I need a neurosurgeon
down here right now.

26:27.653 --> 26:30.654
[ Indistinct talking ]

26:30.656 --> 26:33.591
I think it's
an internal bleed, Natalie!

26:33.593 --> 26:35.292
Natalie: We're slammed up here!
Hold on a second!

26:35.294 --> 26:36.594
Listen.

26:36.595 --> 26:37.895
I'm checking. It's going to
take a few minutes.

26:37.897 --> 26:38.862
Wait! Wait, Natalie!

26:38.864 --> 26:40.664
Ella:
C.T. scan is ready.

26:40.666 --> 26:42.032
All right, great.
Let's move him.

26:42.034 --> 26:43.834
Jesse.
Simple chest tube, right?

26:43.836 --> 26:45.970
Yeah, yeah.
About to start the incision.

26:45.972 --> 26:48.706
Wait. Wait. You're gonna move --
you're leaving?

26:48.708 --> 26:50.174
This patient needs an m.D.,
and we're in code black.

26:50.176 --> 26:51.425
I think you can handle it.

26:51.426 --> 26:52.675
Let's go, let's go.
Let's go, Jesse.

26:52.678 --> 26:54.345
Go, go.
Mama's in the kitchen.

26:57.750 --> 26:59.216
Hey. Focus.

26:59.218 --> 27:00.951
You can do this.

27:01.887 --> 27:02.786
Man: Out of my way!
Come on!

27:17.970 --> 27:20.204
See you. Thanks.

27:22.108 --> 27:24.308
[ Elevator bell dings ]

27:34.954 --> 27:38.722
[ Indistinct talking ]

27:38.724 --> 27:40.391
Medic: Blood pressure.

27:40.393 --> 27:42.159
Man: Great. Hurry up.

27:43.663 --> 27:47.431
Stabilized, let me know
when he's ready.

27:47.433 --> 27:50.401
Got it.
Tube is in.

27:50.403 --> 27:52.269
Vitals are dropping.
Doesn't make sense.

27:52.271 --> 27:53.370
Hang in there, pal,
okay?

27:53.372 --> 27:55.272
Why isn't it working?

27:55.274 --> 27:56.306
What is happening,
please?

27:56.308 --> 27:57.875
Nurse:
Might be a bad chest tube.

27:57.877 --> 27:59.109
I'm gonna need
another chest tube.

27:59.111 --> 28:01.145
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]

28:02.848 --> 28:05.883
I-it's -- it's not the tube.
This one's just stuck.

28:05.885 --> 28:07.251
[ Voice echoing ]

28:14.160 --> 28:15.726
[ Echoing ] Please do something!
He's not breathing!

28:15.728 --> 28:17.094
[ Echoing ] Angus!

28:17.095 --> 28:18.461
Jesse: [ Echoing ] It's stuck in
the fascia of his back.

28:18.464 --> 28:19.797
Get him out of the way!
Grab the tube!

28:19.799 --> 28:22.232
You need to pull!

28:22.234 --> 28:23.734
[ Muffled ] We need to get
the doctor in here!

28:23.736 --> 28:25.069
<i> I'm</i> a doctor.

28:25.071 --> 28:26.704
And you are, too.
Listen.

28:26.706 --> 28:27.838
Listen to my voice, okay?
Okay.

28:27.840 --> 28:29.406
Do you feel it?
Yes.

28:29.407 --> 28:30.973
Just stuck in
the fatty tissue.
Okay.

28:30.976 --> 28:32.409
So we just pull gently.

28:32.411 --> 28:33.744
Okay. Okay.

28:33.746 --> 28:34.845
[ Gasps ]

28:34.847 --> 28:37.715
Ah!

28:37.717 --> 28:40.384
Good job, Dr. pineda.

28:40.386 --> 28:42.319
Your little boy's
gonna be okay.

28:42.321 --> 28:43.387
[ Cries ]

28:43.389 --> 28:44.672
Good job.

28:44.673 --> 28:45.956
I need a 3 of nylon.

28:45.958 --> 28:47.758
Pick this up.

28:47.760 --> 28:49.193
Someone put up
some dressings.

28:49.195 --> 28:50.928
Thank you, thank you.

28:50.930 --> 28:52.162
All right.

28:54.166 --> 28:56.100
[ Alarm dinging ]

29:01.407 --> 29:02.857
Rorish is looking for you.

29:02.858 --> 29:04.308
She canceled the tox screen
on your pregger.

29:04.310 --> 29:05.876
Patient left anyway.

29:05.878 --> 29:07.628
Sorry.

29:07.629 --> 29:09.379
Leanne:
...Which is showing a hyper
dense increased attenuation

29:09.381 --> 29:10.914
in an elliptical pattern,

29:10.915 --> 29:12.448
which is consistent
with an epidural hematoma.

29:12.451 --> 29:13.984
No, do not put me
on hold again!

29:13.986 --> 29:15.786
Dr. rorish,
i know you're angry --

29:15.788 --> 29:18.388
you deliberately ignored
direct instructions

29:18.390 --> 29:20.924
from your
supervising physician.

29:20.926 --> 29:23.527
You said trepidation is
a deadly quality.

29:23.529 --> 29:25.863
I thought I was acting in
the best interest of my patient.

29:25.865 --> 29:27.131
You don't<i> have</i> patients.

29:27.133 --> 29:29.333
You're a first-year --
a first-day resident,

29:29.335 --> 29:32.069
which means every patient
you see is<i> my</i> patient.

29:32.071 --> 29:34.138
If I can't trust you here,
i can't have you here.

29:34.140 --> 29:35.305
Goodbye, Christa.

29:37.009 --> 29:38.142
Wait. What?

29:38.144 --> 29:40.010
Go home. It's over.

29:41.046 --> 29:42.596
Yes, yes, yes,
I'm here.

29:42.597 --> 29:44.147
No, well, someone's gonna
have to drill a hole, then,

29:44.150 --> 29:45.516
because the blood
has to go<i> somewhere!</i>

30:00.032 --> 30:01.064
She fired me.

30:02.067 --> 30:03.784
Did you tell her I knew?

30:03.785 --> 30:05.502
No, Mario,
but thanks for the concern.

30:05.504 --> 30:08.138
Look, I'm sorry, but while you
were busy picking up preschools,

30:08.140 --> 30:09.973
I paid for medical school
driving a truck,

30:09.975 --> 30:10.974
choking on diesel fumes.

30:10.976 --> 30:13.844
Wait, wait, wait.

30:13.846 --> 30:15.145
Diesel fumes!

30:15.147 --> 30:16.413
Oh, my God!
What?

30:16.415 --> 30:18.081
What if
it's carbon monoxide?

30:18.083 --> 30:21.118
Carbon monoxide poisoning
can mimic flu symptoms.

30:21.120 --> 30:22.519
She said she lived
above a boiler room, right?

30:22.521 --> 30:24.955
Oh, my God, Mario,
i could kiss you.

30:24.957 --> 30:26.323
But not really.

30:29.528 --> 30:31.195
[ Keyboard clacking ]

30:32.431 --> 30:34.932
[ Telephone ringing ]

30:37.303 --> 30:39.102
Come on, come on, come on,
come on, come on, come on.

30:39.104 --> 30:41.205
[ Ringing continues ]

30:46.979 --> 30:49.079
[ Ringing continues ]

30:49.081 --> 30:51.148
[ Siren wailing ]

30:55.588 --> 30:58.055
[ Indistinct talking ]

31:02.428 --> 31:04.494
Woman: Let's move, people.

31:05.164 --> 31:06.563
Man:
I.V. And foley are in.

31:06.565 --> 31:08.799
[ Groans ]

31:08.800 --> 31:11.034
Truck ran right over his leg,
broke in at least four places.

31:11.036 --> 31:12.436
Big mid-femur deformity
from the crush.

31:12.438 --> 31:14.171
Neal:
What's your name, sir?

31:14.172 --> 31:15.905
Wayne. I just can't
feel my leg, doc.

31:15.908 --> 31:17.207
Bone's pinching a nerve.
We're gonna help you.

31:19.411 --> 31:20.944
[ Drill whirs ]

31:20.946 --> 31:22.646
I.V., fluids,
20 milligrams morphine stat.

31:22.648 --> 31:23.513
Flying it.

31:23.515 --> 31:24.514
What's that for?

31:24.516 --> 31:26.283
Renovating the suture room.

31:26.285 --> 31:27.384
You're drilling
a burr hole?

31:27.386 --> 31:28.886
Foot cold.
There's no pulse down here.

31:28.888 --> 31:30.087
We got to get
this leg straight.

31:30.089 --> 31:31.221
He's gonna need
that gurney.

31:31.223 --> 31:33.557
Medic: Got it.
Bring it in.

31:33.559 --> 31:35.993
You can't put a hole in that
kid's skull in the E.R., leanne.

31:35.995 --> 31:37.194
You need a neurosurgeon.

31:37.195 --> 31:38.394
It's an epidural bleed.
He's out cold.

31:38.397 --> 31:39.663
I got to drain it.

31:39.664 --> 31:40.930
Medic #2: Line him up.
One, two, three.

31:40.933 --> 31:43.033
[ All grunt ]

31:43.034 --> 31:45.134
Sometimes you just got to be
a cowboy, Neal.

31:45.137 --> 31:47.304
Hey, you're gonna need some help
if you're gonna yank that.

31:47.306 --> 31:48.605
Mario, get over here.

31:50.643 --> 31:52.643
Okay, Wayne, this is gonna help
with the pain.

31:52.645 --> 31:53.644
[ Grunts ]

31:53.646 --> 31:54.945
Man: Phone the cath lab.

31:54.947 --> 31:55.579
Tell them we're on our way.

31:55.581 --> 31:56.647
Mark: Dr. rorish,

31:56.649 --> 31:58.248
you might not be surprised
by this,

31:58.250 --> 31:59.583
but one of your residents
is calling you

31:59.585 --> 32:01.518
from the back of an ambulance
on the 101 freeway.

32:01.520 --> 32:02.552
What?! Who?

32:02.554 --> 32:04.655
Blondie. I got to go.
Christa?

32:04.657 --> 32:06.323
Dr. rorish, it's definitely
carbon monoxide.

32:06.325 --> 32:07.708
They had to break
all the windows.

32:07.709 --> 32:09.092
She's still unconscious.
We're giving her oxygen.

32:09.094 --> 32:10.360
I'm sitting here --

32:10.361 --> 32:11.627
Christa, deep breath.
Give me vitals.

32:11.630 --> 32:14.331
Pulse faint at 120,
b.P. 60 over palp.

32:14.333 --> 32:15.699
Her patient's crashing.

32:15.701 --> 32:17.334
She's pregnant.
You need to get her back here.

32:17.336 --> 32:18.402
She needs
a hyperbaric chamber.

32:18.404 --> 32:19.436
Christa,
what's your e.T.A.?

32:19.438 --> 32:21.104
Not soon.

32:21.106 --> 32:22.339
[ Horn honks ]

32:22.341 --> 32:23.941
You're not gonna like this,
Neal, but...

32:23.943 --> 32:25.375
She has to perform a c-section
on the rig.

32:25.377 --> 32:26.710
Sometimes you got to be
a cowboy, right?

32:26.712 --> 32:29.446
Jesse: Let's do this.

32:29.448 --> 32:31.248
Wait, Christa's gonna do
a c-section?

32:31.250 --> 32:33.583
Mario, focus. I need you
up by his shoulders
to give me leverage.

32:33.585 --> 32:34.985
I'm gonna try
and save his leg.

32:34.987 --> 32:36.987
Christa, listen.

32:36.989 --> 32:38.088
I need you
to tell the medic

32:38.090 --> 32:39.389
to prepare
an emergency surgical kit.

32:39.391 --> 32:41.024
Wait, wait, wait, wait.
I can't do this.

32:41.026 --> 32:42.342
Yes, you can.

32:42.343 --> 32:43.659
You've done
an o.B. Rotation.

32:43.662 --> 32:45.529
You've witnessed
plenty of these.

32:45.531 --> 32:47.164
Medic: Take a deep breath
for me, sir.

32:47.166 --> 32:49.466
Christa, make sure
the patient stays unconscious.

32:49.468 --> 32:51.234
Uh, no danger there.

32:51.236 --> 32:52.202
Okay.

32:52.204 --> 32:53.704
Get ortho ready to go.

32:53.705 --> 32:55.205
Our friend Wayne here is
gonna need an O.R. right after.

32:55.207 --> 32:57.257
Wayne: After what?

32:57.258 --> 32:59.308
Susie, I need you on his pelvis.
Make sure he doesn't slide.

32:59.311 --> 33:01.311
Jesse. Need you over here
for a sec.

33:01.312 --> 33:03.312
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa!
B.P. Dropping!

33:03.315 --> 33:04.614
I need Jesse back,
damn it.

33:04.616 --> 33:06.049
Okay. You got that?

33:06.051 --> 33:07.117
Everybody ready?

33:07.119 --> 33:07.985
Ready for what?

33:07.987 --> 33:08.618
Hold him.

33:08.620 --> 33:10.153
One, two, three.

33:10.155 --> 33:12.656
[ Bones cracking ]
[ Screams ]

33:12.658 --> 33:14.358
[ Horns blaring ]

33:14.360 --> 33:16.460
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]
Pulse is dropping.

33:16.462 --> 33:17.728
Leanne: Okay,
then we got to move fast.

33:17.730 --> 33:19.363
To still have a chance
to save both of them.

33:19.365 --> 33:22.666
Christa, I need you to start
with an abdominal incision

33:22.668 --> 33:24.301
beginning at the umbilicus

33:24.303 --> 33:25.736
and straight down
to the pubic symphysis.

33:25.738 --> 33:27.270
[ Gags ]

33:27.272 --> 33:29.139
Whoa!
Jesse: I need a clean up
in aisle 3.

33:29.141 --> 33:30.574
You need to cut through
all five layers

33:30.576 --> 33:32.309
of the abdominal wall,
including the peritoneum.

33:32.311 --> 33:33.043
I've got this.

33:33.045 --> 33:33.777
[ Drill whirring ]

33:33.778 --> 33:34.510
What is that noise?

33:34.513 --> 33:35.779
Leanne:
Ignore it. Vitals?

33:35.781 --> 33:37.214
Pressure dropping.
Pulse -- 30.

33:37.216 --> 33:39.483
It's okay.
Stay focused.

33:39.485 --> 33:41.485
Start your incision now.

33:41.487 --> 33:44.688
Christa, right under
the abdominal wall,

33:44.690 --> 33:46.089
you're gonna see
something shiny.

33:46.091 --> 33:47.357
That's not the uterus.

33:47.359 --> 33:48.503
It's the bladder.

33:48.504 --> 33:49.648
Careful not to Nick it.

33:49.649 --> 33:50.793
You're gonna want
to reflect it distally,

33:50.796 --> 33:53.030
get it out of your way.

33:53.031 --> 33:55.265
[ Beeping continues ]
Okay, vitals are dropping.

33:55.267 --> 33:57.100
Yeah, I'm almost there.

33:57.102 --> 33:58.235
Leanne?
Almost there.

33:58.237 --> 34:00.570
Okay.
Pulse is dropping.

34:00.572 --> 34:01.605
Leanne,
he's herniating!

34:01.607 --> 34:03.306
I know. Almost.

34:03.308 --> 34:04.341
Christa: Uterus is exposed.

34:04.343 --> 34:06.209
Hang on.
"Hang on"?!

34:06.211 --> 34:08.278
Almost got it.

34:08.280 --> 34:09.146
Is he draining yet?

34:10.215 --> 34:11.548
[ Beeping continues ]

34:11.550 --> 34:13.683
Come on. Come on.
Almost there.

34:13.685 --> 34:16.119
[ Muffled indistinct talking ]

34:19.792 --> 34:21.758
[ Inhales deeply ]

34:21.760 --> 34:23.393
I got it!

34:23.395 --> 34:24.528
Okay, get it in.

34:24.530 --> 34:27.264
Heart rate normalizing.

34:27.266 --> 34:28.065
Pupils...

34:28.067 --> 34:29.400
Reactive.

34:29.401 --> 34:30.734
All right, Christa,

34:30.735 --> 34:32.068
time to make the vertical
incision in the uterus.

34:32.071 --> 34:34.571
Watch the lateral vessels.

34:34.573 --> 34:35.772
Oh, God. [ Sighs ]

34:35.774 --> 34:36.606
Oh!

34:36.608 --> 34:38.275
Okay.

34:38.277 --> 34:40.243
Now, this is gonna happen
very quickly.

34:40.245 --> 34:43.580
I want you to reach your hand
inside as fast as you can,

34:43.582 --> 34:45.282
carefully
feel for the baby.

34:45.284 --> 34:46.283
When?

34:46.285 --> 34:47.350
Have you made
the cut yet?
Yes.

34:47.352 --> 34:48.385
Now!
Now!

34:51.090 --> 34:52.622
All right,
i think I can feel it.

34:53.725 --> 34:55.492
Okay.

34:55.494 --> 34:57.427
I got it.

34:57.429 --> 34:58.628
[ Grunts ]

34:58.630 --> 34:59.729
[ Baby crying ]

34:59.731 --> 35:02.165
Oh! [ Laughs ]

35:02.167 --> 35:03.500
I got her!

35:03.502 --> 35:06.369
[ Crying continues ]

35:08.740 --> 35:11.441
She's so beautiful!

35:11.443 --> 35:12.809
[ Laughing ] Oh, I got her.

35:14.480 --> 35:16.546
Oh, my gosh.

35:19.685 --> 35:21.852
[ Crying continues ]

35:31.463 --> 35:34.197
Okay, kids,
we got one open in O.R.

35:34.199 --> 35:36.366
Mine's stable.
You should go.

35:38.303 --> 35:40.170
All right,
let's move him.

35:40.172 --> 35:41.805
Gurney.

35:41.807 --> 35:43.173
Nurse: Get him up.

35:43.175 --> 35:45.475
Jesse: Okay, guys, let's go!
Go, go!

35:45.477 --> 35:47.544
Move it, move it.
Move aside.

35:56.688 --> 35:59.689
[ Chuckles ]

35:59.691 --> 36:03.660
You think Dr. rorish ignores you
because she doesn't trust you?

36:03.662 --> 36:07.564
It's just the opposite.
She knows you're good.

36:07.566 --> 36:10.333
She's testing
the rest of us.

36:10.335 --> 36:12.102
[ Laughs ]

36:12.103 --> 36:13.870
And I don't think
I'm gonna pass that test.

36:13.872 --> 36:16.406
What are you
talking about?

36:16.408 --> 36:17.874
You know your stuff,
dude.

36:17.876 --> 36:21.545
You just...
Need confidence.

36:29.621 --> 36:31.721
You asked how I got in.

36:31.723 --> 36:35.725
Our dad is
on the hospital board.

36:35.727 --> 36:37.427
My brother
never told anyone.

36:37.429 --> 36:40.797
He thought people wouldn't
take him seriously.

36:40.799 --> 36:42.365
Wouldn't matter anyway.

36:42.367 --> 36:44.234
He was born for this.

36:45.604 --> 36:47.637
I am not like him,
though.

36:47.639 --> 36:49.239
[ Chuckles ]

36:49.241 --> 36:51.374
Then what are you
doing here?

36:51.376 --> 36:53.210
I hated psych.

36:53.212 --> 36:54.945
Hated it.

36:54.947 --> 36:56.880
I wanted something
more exciting.

36:56.882 --> 36:58.648
[ Inhales deeply ]

36:58.650 --> 36:59.950
I wanted what Mike had.

36:59.952 --> 37:02.636
[ Chuckles ]

37:02.637 --> 37:05.321
So when my dad said he could
get me in here, I jumped at it.

37:05.324 --> 37:07.357
Big mistake.

37:07.359 --> 37:09.626
[ Laughs ]

37:09.628 --> 37:13.797
Did you know that they opened
this place up in 1932?

37:13.799 --> 37:15.799
Light bulbs weren't
bright enough back then,

37:15.801 --> 37:17.567
so they put in
all these big windows

37:17.569 --> 37:19.236
so they could see
what they were doing.

37:19.238 --> 37:20.670
[ Chuckles ]

37:20.672 --> 37:22.272
Imagine that.

37:23.775 --> 37:26.376
Hell of a night
for you two.

37:26.378 --> 37:29.779
Started off saving a life,
ended up almost killing someone.

37:29.781 --> 37:31.581
<i>Two</i> people, actually.

37:31.583 --> 37:35.652
I missed
an epidural hematoma.

37:35.654 --> 37:36.987
I missed it, too.

37:36.989 --> 37:39.389
Hm.

37:39.391 --> 37:41.858
Know what that sounds like
to me?

37:41.860 --> 37:44.327
A typical night
in this joint.

37:52.971 --> 37:54.904
[ Crying ]

38:01.580 --> 38:03.680
You did good.

38:05.350 --> 38:07.050
So did you.

38:08.587 --> 38:10.453
We've got her mom
in the hyperbaric chamber,

38:10.455 --> 38:11.755
oxygenated her.

38:11.757 --> 38:12.789
She's gonna make it.

38:12.791 --> 38:14.024
Thank God.

38:14.026 --> 38:16.826
Can I ask you
something personal?

38:18.063 --> 38:21.331
Why are you here?

38:21.333 --> 38:22.832
Pardon?

38:22.834 --> 38:24.668
Med school, internship,

38:24.670 --> 38:26.770
and now the most punishing
residency in the country.

38:26.772 --> 38:27.771
Most people do that
in their 20s.

38:27.773 --> 38:28.805
What made you decide --

38:28.807 --> 38:30.874
my son died.

38:30.876 --> 38:32.842
Stage 4 glio.

38:34.513 --> 38:38.315
You learn a lot
when your kid gets sick.

38:38.317 --> 38:40.450
So I thought maybe
i should make it official.

38:40.452 --> 38:42.652
I got into med school...

38:42.654 --> 38:44.454
[ Chuckles ]

38:44.456 --> 38:46.756
...and here I am.

38:46.758 --> 38:48.858
In my experience,

38:48.860 --> 38:53.430
tragedy either softens you
or hardens you.

38:53.432 --> 38:57.367
For me,
it was the former.

38:57.369 --> 38:58.401
For you,

38:58.403 --> 39:01.871
I suspect...
It was the latter.

39:03.508 --> 39:05.942
You spend enough time
in group therapy sessions,

39:05.944 --> 39:09.045
you start
to recognize it.

39:12.117 --> 39:13.783
Who'd you lose?

39:18.924 --> 39:20.757
Everyone.

39:28.033 --> 39:31.134
You better go home
and get some sleep.

39:31.136 --> 39:33.737
You've got a shift
tonight.

39:33.739 --> 39:35.538
[ Chuckles ]

39:35.540 --> 39:36.806
I do?

39:40.645 --> 39:42.946
¶¶

40:04.503 --> 40:05.969
hi, Ariel.

40:05.971 --> 40:07.537
Hi.

40:07.539 --> 40:09.406
And you must be
aunt Linda.

40:09.408 --> 40:11.408
So nice
to meet you in person.

40:11.410 --> 40:12.675
Thank you for this.

40:12.677 --> 40:14.544
Mm-hmm.

40:14.546 --> 40:15.678
You ready?

40:19.718 --> 40:21.718
I'll wait for you
right here.

40:21.720 --> 40:24.788
¶¶

40:43.608 --> 40:45.108
thank you.

40:50.215 --> 40:52.148
Hi.

40:52.150 --> 40:54.517
I'm Vanessa.

40:54.519 --> 40:56.519
I'm Ariel.

40:58.757 --> 41:00.457
I like your room.

41:00.459 --> 41:02.158
Thanks.

41:06.064 --> 41:08.731
You can come closer
if you want.

41:21.780 --> 41:24.113
It's okay.

41:47.072 --> 41:48.972
Can you hear it?

41:50.976 --> 41:52.742
[ Voice breaking ] Yeah.

41:54.045 --> 41:55.745
I can hear it.

42:00.252 --> 42:02.085
I hear you, daddy.

42:03.889 --> 42:05.855
I hear you.

42:24.943 --> 42:27.010
[ Pager beeping ]

42:28.179 --> 42:30.547
[ Sighs ]
You got to be kidding me.

42:33.652 --> 42:36.619
Every ventilator
i.C.U. Can spare.

42:36.621 --> 42:39.622
Got an apartment fire.
We got 22 in so far.

42:39.624 --> 42:41.591
Burns, smoke inhalation,
broken bones,

42:41.593 --> 42:43.026
and a heart attack.
Got it.

42:43.028 --> 42:44.761
Yeah, we're gonna need
a barrel of morphine.

